[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] The partial alignments can be tabulated in a matrix, where cell (i,j) contains the cost of the optimal alignment of A[1..i] to B[1..j].
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] The cost in cell (i,j) can be calculated by adding the cost of the relevant operations to the cost of its neighboring cells, and selecting the optimum.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Different variants exist, see Smith–Waterman algorithm and Needleman–Wunsch algorithm.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] The **Tower of Hanoi** or **Towers of Hanoi** is a mathematical game or puzzle.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] It consists of three rods, and a number of disks of different sizes which can slide onto any rod.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] The puzzle starts with the disks in a neat stack in ascending order of size on one rod, the smallest at the top, thus making a conical shape.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] S(n, h, t) := solution to a problem consisting of n disks that are to be moved from rod h to rod t.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] For n=1 the problem is trivial, namely S(1,h,t) = "move a disk from rod h to rod t" (there is only one disk left).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] The number of moves required by this solution is 2*n* − 1.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] If the objective is to **maximize** the number of moves (without cycling) then the dynamic programming functional equation is slightly more complicated and 3*n* − 1 moves are required.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] A famous puzzle relates to dropping eggs from a building to determine at which height they start to break.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] terminology, in which the first floor is at ground level).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] If only one egg is available and we wish to be sure of obtaining the right result, the experiment can be carried out in only one way.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Drop the egg from the first-floor window; if it survives, drop it from the second-floor window.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] In the worst case, this method may require 36 droppings.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] What is the lowest number of egg-droppings that is guaranteed to work in all cases?
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] For instance, *s* = (2,6) indicates that two test eggs are available and 6 (consecutive) floors are yet to be tested.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] The initial state of the process is *s* = (*N*,*H*) where *N* denotes the number of test eggs available at the commencement of the experiment.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] The process terminates either when there are no more test eggs (*n* = 0) or when *k* = 0, whichever occurs first.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] If termination occurs at state *s* = (0,*k*) and *k* > 0, then the test failed.
