[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] This can be improved to $O(nk\log k)$ time by binary searching on the optimal x in the above recurrence, since $W(n-1,x-1)$ is increasing in x while $W(n,k-x)$ is decreasing in x , thus a local minimum of $\max(W(n-1,x-1),W(n,k-x))$ is a global minimum.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Also, by storing the optimal x for each cell in the DP table and referring to its value for the previous cell, the optimal x for each cell can be found in constant time, improving it to $O(nk)$ time.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Let k be the total number of floors such that the eggs break when dropped from the k th floor (The example above is equivalent to taking $k=37$ ).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Let m be the minimum floor from which the egg must be dropped to be broken.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Let $f(t,n)$ be the maximum number of values of m that are distinguishable using t tries and n eggs.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Let a be the floor from which the first egg is dropped in the optimal strategy.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] If the first egg broke, m is from 1 to a and distinguishable using at most $t-1$ tries and $n-1$ eggs.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] If the first egg did not break, m is from $a+1$ to k and distinguishable using $t-1$ tries and n eggs.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Then the problem is equivalent to finding the minimum x such that $f(x,n)\geq k$ .
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] To do so, we could compute $\{f(t,i):0\leq i\leq n\}$ in order of increasing t , which would take $O(nx)$ time.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Thus, if we separately handle the case of $n=1$ , the algorithm would take $O(n{\sqrt {k}})$ time.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] But the recurrence relation can in fact be solved, giving $f(t,n)=\sum _{i=0}^{n}{\binom {t}{i}}$ , which can be computed in $O(n)$ time using the identity ${\binom {t}{i+1}}={\binom {t}{i}}{\frac {t-i}{i+1}}$ for all $i\geq 0$ .
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Since $f(t,n)\leq f(t+1,n)$ for all $t\geq 0$ , we can binary search on t to find x , giving an $O(n\log k)$ algorithm.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Matrix chain multiplication is a well-known example that demonstrates utility of dynamic programming.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] For example, engineering applications often have to multiply a chain of matrices.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] It is not surprising to find matrices of large dimensions, for example 100×100.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Matrix multiplication is not commutative, but is associative; and we can multiply only two matrices at a time.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] There are numerous ways to multiply this chain of matrices.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] They will all produce the same final result, however they will take more or less time to compute, based on which particular matrices are multiplied.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] If matrix A has dimensions m×n and matrix B has dimensions n×q, then matrix C=A×B will have dimensions m×q, and will require m*n*q scalar multiplications (using a simplistic matrix multiplication algorithm for purposes of illustration).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] For example, let us multiply matrices A, B and C.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Let us assume that their dimensions are m×n, n×p, and p×s, respectively.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] (A×B)×C This order of matrix multiplication will require mnp + mps scalar calculations.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] So, the first way to multiply the chain will require 1,000,000 + 1,000,000 calculations.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] The second way will require only 10,000 + 100,000 calculations.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Obviously, the second way is faster, and we should multiply the matrices using that arrangement of parenthesis.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Therefore, our conclusion is that the order of parenthesis matters, and that our task is to find the optimal order of parenthesis.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] At this point, we have several choices, one of which is to design a dynamic programming algorithm that will split the problem into overlapping problems and calculate the optimal arrangement of parenthesis.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] The dynamic programming solution is presented below.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Let's call m[i,j] the minimum number of scalar multiplications needed to multiply a chain of matrices from matrix i to matrix j (i.e.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] We split the chain at some matrix k, such that i <= k < j, and try to find out which combination produces minimum m[i,j].
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] So far, we have calculated values for all possible *m*[*i*, *j*], the minimum number of calculations to multiply a chain from matrix *i* to matrix *j*, and we have recorded the corresponding "split point"*s*[*i*, *j*].
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] This algorithm will produce "tables" *m*[, ] and *s*[, ] that will have entries for all possible values of i and j.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] The final solution for the entire chain is m[1, n], with corresponding split at s[1, n].
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Unraveling the solution will be recursive, starting from the top and continuing until we reach the base case, i.e. multiplication of single matrices.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Therefore, the next step is to actually split the chain, i.e. to place the parenthesis where they (optimally) belong.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Of course, this algorithm is not useful for actual multiplication.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] This algorithm is just a user-friendly way to see what the result looks like.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] The term *dynamic programming* was originally used in the 1940s by Richard Bellman to describe the process of solving problems where one needs to find the best decisions one after another.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] By 1953, he refined this to the modern meaning, referring specifically to nesting smaller decision problems inside larger decisions, and the field was thereafter recognized by the IEEE as a systems analysis and engineering topic.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Bellman's contribution is remembered in the name of the Bellman equation, a central result of dynamic programming which restates an optimization problem in recursive form.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] The word *dynamic* was chosen by Bellman to capture the time-varying aspect of the problems, and because it sounded impressive.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] The word *programming* referred to the use of the method to find an optimal *program*, in the sense of a military schedule for training or logistics.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] This usage is the same as that in the phrases *linear programming* and *mathematical programming*, a synonym for mathematical optimization.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] The above explanation of the origin of the term may be inaccurate: According to Russell and Norvig, the above story "cannot be strictly true, because his first paper using the term (Bellman, 1952) appeared before Wilson became Secretary of Defense in 1953." Also, Harold J.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/dynamic-programming] Kushner stated in a speech that, "On the other hand, when I asked [Bellman] the same question, he replied that he was trying to upstage Dantzig's linear programming by adding dynamic.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] In computational linguistics and computer science, **edit distance** is a string metric, i.e. a way of quantifying how dissimilar two strings (e.g., words) are to one another, that is measured by counting the minimum number of operations required to transform one string into the other.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Edit distances find applications in natural language processing, where automatic spelling correction can determine candidate corrections for a misspelled word by selecting words from a dictionary that have a low distance to the word in question.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] In bioinformatics, it can be used to quantify the similarity of DNA sequences, which can be viewed as strings of the letters A, C, G and T.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Different definitions of an edit distance use different sets of like operations.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Levenshtein distance operations are the removal, insertion, or substitution of a character in the string.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Being the most common metric, the term *Levenshtein distance* is often used interchangeably with *edit distance*.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Different types of edit distance allow different sets of string operations.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Some edit distances are defined as a parameterizable metric calculated with a specific set of allowed edit operations, and each operation is assigned a cost (possibly infinite).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] This is further generalized by DNA sequence alignment algorithms such as the Smith–Waterman algorithm, which make an operation's cost depend on where it is applied.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Given two strings a and b on an alphabet Σ (e.g. the set of ASCII characters, the set of bytes [0..255], etc.), the edit distance d(a, b) is the minimum-weight series of edit operations that transforms a into b.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] In Levenshtein's original definition, each of these operations has unit cost (except that substitution of a character by itself has zero cost), so the Levenshtein distance is equal to the minimum *number* of operations required to transform a to b.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] A more general definition associates non-negative weight functions wins(x), wdel(x) and wsub(x, y) with the operations.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Additional primitive operations have been suggested.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Damerau–Levenshtein distance counts as a single edit a common mistake: **transposition** of two adjacent characters, formally characterized by an operation that changes uxyv into uyxv.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] For the task of correcting OCR output, **merge** and **split** operations have been used which replace a single character into a pair of them or vice versa.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Other variants of edit distance are obtained by restricting the set of operations.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Longest common subsequence (LCS) distance is edit distance with insertion and deletion as the only two edit operations, both at unit cost.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Similarly, by only allowing substitutions (again at unit cost), Hamming distance is obtained; this must be restricted to equal-length strings.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Jaro–Winkler distance can be obtained from an edit distance where only transpositions are allowed.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] The Levenshtein distance between "kitten" and "sitting" is 3.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] for a total cost/distance of 5 operations.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] ) = 0 if and only if a=b, since each string can be trivially transformed to itself using exactly zero operations.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] , since this would require at least one operation at non-zero cost.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] ) by equality of the cost of each operation and its inverse.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Levenshtein distance and LCS distance with unit cost satisfy the above conditions, and therefore the metric axioms.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Variants of edit distance that are not proper metrics have also been considered in the literature.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] The first algorithm for computing minimum edit distance between a pair of strings was published by Damerau in 1964.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] This algorithm can be generalized to handle transpositions by adding another term in the recursive clause's minimization.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] The straightforward, recursive way of evaluating this recurrence takes exponential time.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Therefore, it is usually computed using a dynamic programming algorithm that is commonly credited to Wagner and Fischer, although it has a history of multiple invention.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] After completion of the Wagner–Fischer algorithm, a minimal sequence of edit operations can be read off as a backtrace of the operations used during the dynamic programming algorithm starting at $d_{mn}$ .
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] This algorithm has a time complexity of Θ(mn) where m and n are the lengths of the strings.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] When the full dynamic programming table is constructed, its space complexity is also Θ(mn); this can be improved to Θ(min(m,n)) by observing that at any instant, the algorithm only requires two rows (or two columns) in memory.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] However, this optimization makes it impossible to read off the minimal series of edit operations.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] A linear-space solution to this problem is offered by Hirschberg's algorithm.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] A general recursive divide-and-conquer framework for solving such recurrences and extracting an optimal sequence of operations cache-efficiently in space linear in the size of the input is given by Chowdhury, Le, and Ramachandran.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Improving on the Wagner–Fisher algorithm described above, Ukkonen describes several variants, one of which takes two strings and a maximum edit distance s, and returns min(s, d).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] It achieves this by only computing and storing a part of the dynamic programming table around its diagonal.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] This algorithm takes time O(s×min(m,n)), where m and n are the lengths of the strings.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Space complexity is O(s2) or O(s), depending on whether the edit sequence needs to be read off.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Further improvements by Landau, Myers, and Schmidt [1] give an O(s2 + max(m,n)) time algorithm.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] For a finite alphabet and edit costs which are multiples of each other, the fastest known exact algorithm is of Masek and Paterson having worst case runtime of O(nm/logn).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Various algorithms exist that solve problems beside the computation of distance between a pair of strings, to solve related types of problems.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] A generalization of the edit distance between strings is the language edit distance between a string and a language, usually a formal language.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Instead of considering the edit distance between one string and another, the language edit distance is the minimum edit distance that can be attained between a fixed string and *any* string taken from a set of strings.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] More formally, for any language *L* and string *x* over an alphabet Σ, the *language edit distance* d(*L*, *x*) is given by $d(L,x)=\min _{y\in L}d(x,y)$ , where $d(x,y)$ is the string edit distance.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] When the language *L* is context free, there is a cubic time dynamic programming algorithm proposed by Aho and Peterson in 1972 which computes the language edit distance.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] For less expressive families of grammars, such as the regular grammars, faster algorithms exist for computing the edit distance.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/edit-distance] Language edit distance has found many diverse applications, such as RNA folding, error correction, and solutions to the Optimum Stack Generation problem.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] A **longest common subsequence** (**LCS**) is the longest subsequence common to all sequences in a set of sequences (often just two sequences).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] It differs from the longest common substring: unlike substrings, subsequences are not required to occupy consecutive positions within the original sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] The problem of computing longest common subsequences is a classic computer science problem.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Because it is polynomial and has an efficient algorithm to solve it, it is employed to compare data and merge changes to files in programs such as the `diff` utility and revision control systems such as Git.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] It has similar applications in computational linguistics and bioinformatics.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] For example, consider the sequences (ABCD) and (ACBAD).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] They have five length-2 common subsequences: (AB), (AC), (AD), (BD), and (CD); two length-3 common subsequences: (ABD) and (ACD); and no longer common subsequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] So (ABD) and (ACD) are their longest common subsequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] For the general case of an arbitrary number of input sequences, the problem is NP-hard.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] When the number of sequences is constant, the problem is solvable in polynomial time by dynamic programming.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] For the case of two sequences of *n* and *m* elements, the running time of the dynamic programming approach is O(*n* × *m*).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] There exist methods with lower complexity, which often depend on the length of the LCS, the size of the alphabet, or both.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] The LCS is not necessarily unique; in the worst case, the number of common subsequences is exponential in the lengths of the inputs, so the algorithmic complexity of listing *all* common subsequences must be at least exponential.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] The LCS problem has an optimal substructure: the problem can be broken down into smaller, simpler subproblems, which can, in turn, be broken down into simpler subproblems, and so on, until, finally, the solution becomes trivial.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] LCS in particular has overlapping subproblems: the solutions to high-level subproblems often reuse solutions to lower level subproblems.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Problems with these two properties are amenable to dynamic programming approaches, in which subproblem solutions are memoized, that is, the solutions of subproblems are saved for reuse.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] The prefix *S**n* of *S* is defined as the first *n* characters of *S*.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Let *LCS*(*X*, *Y*) be a function that computes a longest subsequence common to *X* and *Y*.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Such a function has two interesting properties.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] For example, *LCS*("ABCDEFG","BCDGK") is the longest string among *LCS*("ABCDEFG","BCDG") and *LCS*("ABCDEF","BCDGK"); if both happened to be of equal length, one of them could be chosen arbitrarily.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Let ${\mathit {LCS}}(X_{i},Y_{j})$ represent the set of longest common subsequence of prefixes $X_{i}$ and $Y_{j}$ .
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] This set of sequences is given by the following.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] If they are equal, then the sequence ${\mathit {LCS}}(X_{i-1},Y_{j-1})$ is extended by that element, $x_{i}$ .
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] If they are not equal, then the longest among the two sequences, ${\mathit {LCS}}(X_{i},Y_{j-1})$ , and ${\mathit {LCS}}(X_{i-1},Y_{j})$ , is retained.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] (If they are the same length, but not identical, then both are retained.) The base case, when either $X_{i}$ or $Y_{i}$ is empty, is the empty string, $\epsilon$ .
