[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] The function below takes as input sequences `X[1..m]` and `Y[1..n]`, computes the LCS between `X[1..i]` and `Y[1..j]` for all `1 ≤ i ≤ m` and `1 ≤ j ≤ n`, and stores it in `C[i,j]`.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] `C[m,n]` will contain the length of the LCS of `X` and `Y`.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Alternatively, memoization could be used.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] The following function backtracks the choices taken when computing the `C` table.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] If the last characters in the prefixes are equal, they must be in an LCS.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] If not, check what gave the largest LCS of keeping $x_{i}$ and $y_{j}$ , and make the same choice.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Just choose one if they were equally long.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] If choosing $x_{i}$ and $y_{j}$ would give an equally long result, read out both resulting subsequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] This is returned as a set by this function.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Notice that this function is not polynomial, as it might branch in almost every step if the strings are similar.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] This function will backtrack through the C matrix, and print the diff between the two sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Notice that you will get a different answer if you exchange `≥` and `<`, with `>` and `≤` below.
