[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] If not, we go up or left, depending on which cell has a higher number.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Several optimizations can be made to the algorithm above to speed it up for real-world cases.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] The C matrix in the naive algorithm grows quadratically with the lengths of the sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] For two 100-item sequences, a 10,000-item matrix would be needed, and 10,000 comparisons would need to be done.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] In most real-world cases, especially source code diffs and patches, the beginnings and ends of files rarely change, and almost certainly not both at the same time.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] If only a few items have changed in the middle of the sequence, the beginning and end can be eliminated.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] This reduces not only the memory requirements for the matrix, but also the number of comparisons that must be done.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] In the best-case scenario, a sequence with no changes, this optimization would eliminate the need for the C matrix.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] In the worst-case scenario, a change to the very first and last items in the sequence, only two additional comparisons are performed.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Most of the time taken by the naive algorithm is spent performing comparisons between items in the sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] For textual sequences such as source code, you want to view lines as the sequence elements instead of single characters.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] This can mean comparisons of relatively long strings for each step in the algorithm.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Two optimizations can be made that can help to reduce the time these comparisons consume.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] A hash function or checksum can be used to reduce the size of the strings in the sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] That is, for source code where the average line is 60 or more characters long, the hash or checksum for that line might be only 8 to 40 characters long.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Additionally, the randomized nature of hashes and checksums would guarantee that comparisons would short-circuit faster, as lines of source code will rarely be changed at the beginning.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] There are three primary drawbacks to this optimization.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] First, an amount of time needs to be spent beforehand to precompute the hashes for the two sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Second, additional memory needs to be allocated for the new hashed sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] However, in comparison to the naive algorithm used here, both of these drawbacks are relatively minimal.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] The third drawback is that of collisions.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Since the checksum or hash is not guaranteed to be unique, there is a small chance that two different items could be reduced to the same hash.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] This is unlikely in source code, but it is possible.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] A cryptographic hash would therefore be far better suited for this optimization, as its entropy is going to be significantly greater than that of a simple checksum.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] However, the benefits may not be worth the setup and computational requirements of a cryptographic hash for small sequence lengths.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] If only the length of the LCS is required, the matrix can be reduced to a $2\times \min(n,m)$ matrix, or to a $\min(m,n)+1$ vector as the dynamic programming approach requires only the current and previous columns of the matrix.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Hirschberg's algorithm allows the construction of the optimal sequence itself in the same quadratic time and linear space bounds.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Chowdhury and Ramachandran devised a quadratic-time linear-space algorithm for finding the LCS length along with an optimal sequence which runs faster than Hirschberg's algorithm in practice due to its superior cache performance.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] The algorithm has an asymptotically optimal cache complexity under the Ideal cache model.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Interestingly, the algorithm itself is cache-oblivious meaning that it does not make any choices based on the cache parameters (e.g., cache size and cache line size) of the machine.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Several algorithms exist that run faster than the presented dynamic programming approach.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] One of them is Hunt–Szymanski algorithm, which typically runs in $O((n+r)\log(n))$ time (for $n>m$ ), where r is the number of matches between the two sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] For problems with a bounded alphabet size, the Method of Four Russians can be used to reduce the running time of the dynamic programming algorithm by a logarithmic factor.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Beginning with Chvátal & Sankoff (1975), a number of researchers have investigated the behavior of the longest common subsequence length when the two given strings are drawn randomly from the same alphabet.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] When the alphabet size is constant, the expected length of the LCS is proportional to the length of the two strings, and the constants of proportionality (depending on alphabet size) are known as the Chvátal–Sankoff constants.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Their exact values are not known, but upper and lower bounds on their values have been proven, and it is known that they grow inversely proportionally to the square root of the alphabet size.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] Simplified mathematical models of the longest common subsequence problem have been shown to be controlled by the Tracy–Widom distribution.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] For decades, it had been considered folklore that the longest palindromic subsequence of a string could be computed by finding the longest common subsequence between the string and its reversal, using the classical dynamic programming approach introduced by Wagner and Fischer.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-subsequence] However, a formal proof of the correctness of this method was only established in 2024 by Brodal, Fagerberg, and Moldrup Rysgaard.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] In computer science, a **longest common substring** of two or more strings is a longest string that is a substring of all of them.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] There may be more than one longest common substring.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] Applications include data deduplication and plagiarism detection.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] Unlike the longest common subsequence problem, which finds insertions or deletions within the common text, the longest common substring problem seeks a contiguous substring shared by both texts.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] The picture shows two strings where the problem has multiple solutions.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] Although the substring occurrences always overlap, it is impossible to obtain a longer common substring by "uniting" them.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] The strings "ABABC", "BABCA" and "ABCBA" have only one longest common substring, viz.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] Other common substrings are "A", "AB", "B", "BA", "BC" and "C".
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] Given two strings, S of length m and T of length n , find a longest string which is substring of both S and T .
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] A generalization is the *k*-**common substring problem**.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] Find for each $2\leq k\leq K$ , a longest string which occurs as substring of at least k strings.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] One can find the lengths and starting positions of the longest common substrings of S and T in $\Theta$ $(n+m)$ time with the help of a generalized suffix tree.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] A faster algorithm can be achieved in the word RAM model of computation if the size $\sigma$ of the input alphabet is in $2^{o\left({\sqrt {\log(n+m)}}\right)}$ .
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] In particular, this algorithm runs in ${\textstyle O\left((n+m)\log \sigma /{\sqrt {\log(n+m)}}\right)}$ time using $O\left((n+m)\log \sigma /\log(n+m)\right)$ space.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] Solving the problem by dynamic programming costs $\Theta (nm)$ .
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] The solutions to the generalized problem take $\Theta (n_{1}+\cdots +n_{K})$ space and $\Theta (n_{1}\cdots n_{K})$ time with dynamic programming and take $\Theta (n_{1}+\cdots +n_{K})$ time with a generalized suffix tree.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] The longest common substrings of a set of strings can be found by building a generalized suffix tree for the strings, and then finding the deepest internal nodes which have leaf nodes from all the strings in the subtree below it.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] The figure on the right is the suffix tree for the strings "ABAB", "BABA" and "ABBA", padded with unique string terminators, to become "ABAB$0", "BABA$1" and "ABBA$2".
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] The nodes representing "A", "B", "AB" and "BA" all have descendant leaves from all of the strings, numbered 0, 1 and 2.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] Building the suffix tree takes $\Theta (N)$ time (if the size of the alphabet is constant).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] If the tree is traversed from the bottom up with a bit vector telling which strings are seen below each node, the k-common substring problem can be solved in $\Theta (NK)$ time.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] If the suffix tree is prepared for constant time lowest common ancestor retrieval, it can be solved in $\Theta (N)$ time.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] The array `L` stores the length of the longest common suffix of the prefixes `S[1..i]` and `T[1..j]` which *end at position* `i` and `j`, respectively.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] The variable `z` is used to hold the length of the longest common substring found so far.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] The set `ret` is used to hold the set of strings which are of length `z`.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] The set `ret` can be saved efficiently by just storing the index `i`, which is the last character of the longest common substring (of size z) instead of `S[(i-z+1)..i]`.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/longest-common-substring] Thus all the longest common substrings would be, for each i in `ret`, `S[(ret[i]-z)..(ret[i])]`.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] In bioinformatics, a **sequence alignment** is a way of arranging the sequences of DNA, RNA, or protein to identify regions of similarity that may be a consequence of functional, structural, or evolutionary relationships between the sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Aligned sequences of nucleotide or amino acid residues are typically represented as rows within a matrix.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Gaps are inserted between the residues so that identical or similar characters are aligned in successive columns.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Sequence alignments are also used for non-biological sequences such as calculating the distance cost between strings in a natural language, or to display financial data.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] If two sequences in an alignment share a common ancestor, mismatches can be interpreted as point mutations and gaps as indels (that is, insertion or deletion mutations) introduced in one or both lineages in the time since they diverged from one another.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] In sequence alignments of proteins, the degree of similarity between amino acids occupying a particular position in the sequence can be interpreted as a rough measure of how conserved a particular region or sequence motif is among lineages.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The absence of substitutions, or the presence of only very conservative substitutions (that is, the substitution of amino acids whose side chains have similar biochemical properties) in a particular region of the sequence, suggest that this region has structural or functional importance.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Although DNA and RNA nucleotide bases are more similar to each other than are amino acids, the conservation of base pairs can indicate a similar functional or structural role.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Very short or very similar sequences can be aligned by hand.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] However, most interesting problems require the alignment of lengthy, highly variable or extremely numerous sequences that cannot be aligned solely by human effort.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Various algorithms were devised to produce high-quality sequence alignments, and occasionally in adjusting the final results to reflect patterns that are difficult to represent algorithmically (especially in the case of nucleotide sequences).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Computational approaches to sequence alignment generally fall into two categories: *global alignments* and *local alignments*.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Calculating a global alignment is a form of global optimization that "forces" the alignment to span the entire length of all query sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] By contrast, local alignments identify regions of similarity within long sequences that are often widely divergent overall.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Local alignments are often preferable, but can be more difficult to calculate because of the additional challenge of identifying the regions of similarity.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] A variety of computational algorithms have been applied to the sequence alignment problem.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] These include slow but formally correct methods like dynamic programming.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] These also include efficient, heuristic algorithms or probabilistic methods designed for large-scale database search, that do not guarantee to find best matches.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Alignments are commonly represented both graphically and in text format.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] In almost all sequence alignment representations, sequences are written in rows arranged so that aligned residues appear in successive columns.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] In text formats, aligned columns containing identical or similar characters are indicated with a system of conservation symbols.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] As in the image above, an asterisk or pipe symbol is used to show identity between two columns; other less common symbols include a colon for conservative substitutions and a period for semiconservative substitutions.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Many sequence visualization programs also use color to display information about the properties of the individual sequence elements; in DNA and RNA sequences, this equates to assigning each nucleotide its own color.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] In protein alignments, such as the one in the image above, color is often used to indicate amino acid properties to aid in judging the conservation of a given amino acid substitution.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Sequence alignments can be stored in a wide variety of text-based file formats, many of which were originally developed in conjunction with a specific alignment program or implementation.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Most web-based tools allow a limited number of input and output formats, such as FASTA format and GenBank format and the output is not easily editable.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Several conversion programs that provide graphical and/or command line interfaces are available, such as READSEQ and EMBOSS.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] There are also several programming packages which provide this conversion functionality, such as BioPython, BioRuby and BioPerl.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The SAM/BAM files use the CIGAR (Compact Idiosyncratic Gapped Alignment Report) string format to represent an alignment of a sequence to a reference by encoding a sequence of events (e.g. match/mismatch, insertions, deletions).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The original CIGAR format from the exonerate alignment program did not distinguish between mismatches or matches with the M character.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The SAMv1 spec document defines newer CIGAR codes.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] In most cases it is preferred to use the '=' and 'X' characters to denote matches or mismatches rather than the older 'M' character, which is ambiguous.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Global alignments, which attempt to align every residue in every sequence, are most useful when the sequences in the query set are similar and of roughly equal size.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] (This does not mean global alignments cannot start and/or end in gaps.) A general global alignment technique is the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm, which is based on dynamic programming.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Local alignments are more useful for dissimilar sequences that are suspected to contain regions of similarity or similar sequence motifs within their larger sequence context.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The Smith–Waterman algorithm is a general local alignment method based on the same dynamic programming scheme but with additional choices to start and end at any place.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Hybrid methods, known as semi-global or "glocal" (short for **glo**bal-lo**cal**) methods, search for the best possible partial alignment of the two sequences (in other words, a combination of one or both starts and one or both ends is stated to be aligned).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] This can be especially useful when the downstream part of one sequence overlaps with the upstream part of the other sequence.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] In this case, neither global nor local alignment is entirely appropriate: a global alignment would attempt to force the alignment to extend beyond the region of overlap, while a local alignment might not fully cover the region of overlap.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Another case where semi-global alignment is useful is when one sequence is short (for example a gene sequence) and the other is very long (for example a chromosome sequence).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] In that case, the short sequence should be globally (fully) aligned but only a local (partial) alignment is desired for the long sequence.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Fast expansion of genetic data challenges speed of current DNA sequence alignment algorithms.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Essential needs for an efficient and accurate method for DNA variant discovery demand innovative approaches for parallel processing in real time.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Optical computing approaches have been suggested as promising alternatives to the current electrical implementations, yet their applicability remains to be tested [1].
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Pairwise sequence alignment methods are used to find the best-matching piecewise (local or global) alignments of two query sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Pairwise alignments can only be used between two sequences at a time, but they are efficient to calculate and are often used for methods that do not require extreme precision (such as searching a database for sequences with high similarity to a query).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The three primary methods of producing pairwise alignments are dot-matrix methods, dynamic programming, and word methods; however, multiple sequence alignment techniques can also align pairs of sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Although each method has its individual strengths and weaknesses, all three pairwise methods have difficulty with highly repetitive sequences of low information content - especially where the number of repetitions differ in the two sequences to be aligned.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] One way of quantifying the utility of a given pairwise alignment is the 'maximal unique match' (MUM), or the longest subsequence that occurs in both query sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Longer MUM sequences typically reflect closer relatedness in the multiple sequence alignment of genomes in computational biology.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Identification of MUMs and other potential anchors, is the first step in larger alignment systems such as MUMmer.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Anchors are the areas between two genomes where they are highly similar.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] To understand what a MUM is we can break down each word in the acronym.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Match implies that the substring occurs in both sequences to be aligned.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Unique means that the substring occurs only once in each sequence.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Finally, maximal states that the substring is not part of another larger string that fulfills both prior requirements.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The idea behind this, is that long sequences that match exactly and occur only once in each genome are almost certainly part of the global alignment.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The dot-matrix approach, which implicitly produces a family of alignments for individual sequence regions, is qualitative and conceptually simple, though time-consuming to analyze on a large scale.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] In the absence of noise, it can be easy to visually identify certain sequence features—such as insertions, deletions, repeats, or inverted repeats—from a dot-matrix plot.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] To construct a dot-matrix plot, the two sequences are written along the top row and leftmost column of a two-dimensional matrix and a dot is placed at any point where the characters in the appropriate columns match—this is a typical recurrence plot.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Some implementations vary the size or intensity of the dot depending on the degree of similarity of the two characters, to accommodate conservative substitutions.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The dot plots of very closely related sequences will appear as a single line along the matrix's main diagonal.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Problems with dot plots as an information display technique include: noise, lack of clarity, non-intuitiveness, difficulty extracting match summary statistics and match positions on the two sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] There is also much wasted space where the match data is inherently duplicated across the diagonal and most of the actual area of the plot is taken up by either empty space or noise, and, finally, dot-plots are limited to two sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] None of these limitations apply to Miropeats alignment diagrams but they have their own particular flaws.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Dot plots can also be used to assess repetitiveness in a single sequence.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] A sequence can be plotted against itself and regions that share significant similarities will appear as lines off the main diagonal.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] This effect occurs when a protein consists of multiple similar structural domains.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The technique of dynamic programming can be applied to produce global alignments via the Needleman-Wunsch algorithm, and local alignments via the Smith-Waterman algorithm.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] In typical usage, protein alignments use a substitution matrix to assign scores to amino-acid matches or mismatches, and a gap penalty for matching an amino acid in one sequence to a gap in the other.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] DNA and RNA alignments may use a scoring matrix, but in practice often simply assign a positive match score, a negative mismatch score, and a negative gap penalty.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] (In standard dynamic programming, the score of each amino acid position is independent of the identity of its neighbors, and therefore base stacking effects are not taken into account.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] However, it is possible to account for such effects by modifying the algorithm.) A common extension to standard linear gap costs are affine gap costs.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Here two different gap penalties are applied for opening a gap and for extending a gap.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Typically the former is much larger than the latter, e.g. -10 for gap open and -2 for gap extension.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] This results in fewer gaps in an alignment and residues and gaps are kept together, traits more representative of biological sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The Gotoh algorithm implements affine gap costs by using three matrices.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Dynamic programming can be useful in aligning nucleotide to protein sequences, a task complicated by the need to take into account frameshift mutations (usually insertions or deletions).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The framesearch method produces a series of global or local pairwise alignments between a query nucleotide sequence and a search set of protein sequences, or vice versa.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Its ability to evaluate frameshifts offset by an arbitrary number of nucleotides makes the method useful for sequences containing large numbers of indels, which can be very difficult to align with more efficient heuristic methods.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] In practice, the method requires large amounts of computing power or a system whose architecture is specialized for dynamic programming.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The BLAST and EMBOSS suites provide basic tools for creating translated alignments (though some of these approaches take advantage of side-effects of sequence searching capabilities of the tools).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] More general methods are available from open-source software such as GeneWise.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The dynamic programming method is guaranteed to find an optimal alignment given a particular scoring function; however, identifying a good scoring function is often an empirical rather than a theoretical matter.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Although dynamic programming is extensible to more than two sequences, it is prohibitively slow for large numbers of sequences or extremely long sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Word methods, also known as *k*-tuple methods, are heuristic methods that are not guaranteed to find an optimal alignment solution, but are significantly more efficient than dynamic programming.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] These methods are especially useful in large-scale database searches where it is understood that a large proportion of the candidate sequences will have essentially no significant match with the query sequence.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Word methods are best known for their implementation in the database search tools FASTA and the BLAST family.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Word methods identify a series of short, nonoverlapping subsequences ("words") in the query sequence that are then matched to candidate database sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The relative positions of the word in the two sequences being compared are subtracted to obtain an offset; this will indicate a region of alignment if multiple distinct words produce the same offset.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Only if this region is detected do these methods apply more sensitive alignment criteria; thus, many unnecessary comparisons with sequences of no appreciable similarity are eliminated.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] In the FASTA method, the user defines a value *k* to use as the word length with which to search the database.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The method is slower but more sensitive at lower values of *k*, which are also preferred for searches involving a very short query sequence.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The BLAST family of search methods provides a number of algorithms optimized for particular types of queries, such as searching for distantly related sequence matches.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] BLAST was developed to provide a faster alternative to FASTA without sacrificing much accuracy; like FASTA, BLAST uses a word search of length *k*, but evaluates only the most significant word matches, rather than every word match as does FASTA.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Most BLAST implementations use a fixed default word length that is optimized for the query and database type, and that is changed only under special circumstances, such as when searching with repetitive or very short query sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Implementations can be found via a number of web portals, such as EMBL FASTA and NCBI BLAST.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Multiple sequence alignment is an extension of pairwise alignment to incorporate more than two sequences at a time.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Multiple alignment methods try to align all of the sequences in a given query set.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Multiple alignments are often used in identifying conserved sequence regions across a group of sequences hypothesized to be evolutionarily related.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Such conserved sequence motifs can be used in conjunction with structural and mechanistic information to locate the catalytic active sites of enzymes.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Alignments are also used to aid in establishing evolutionary relationships by constructing phylogenetic trees.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Multiple sequence alignments are computationally difficult to produce and most formulations of the problem lead to NP-complete combinatorial optimization problems.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Nevertheless, the utility of these alignments in bioinformatics has led to the development of a variety of methods suitable for aligning three or more sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The technique of dynamic programming is theoretically applicable to any number of sequences; however, because it is computationally expensive in both time and memory, it is rarely used for more than three or four sequences in its most basic form.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] This method requires constructing the *n*-dimensional equivalent of the sequence matrix formed from two sequences, where *n* is the number of sequences in the query.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Standard dynamic programming is first used on all pairs of query sequences and then the "alignment space" is filled in by considering possible matches or gaps at intermediate positions, eventually constructing an alignment essentially between each two-sequence alignment.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Although this technique is computationally expensive, its guarantee of a global optimum solution is useful in cases where only a few sequences need to be aligned accurately.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] One method for reducing the computational demands of dynamic programming, which relies on the "sum of pairs" objective function, has been implemented in the MSA software package.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Progressive, hierarchical, or tree methods generate a multiple sequence alignment by first aligning the most similar sequences and then adding successively less related sequences or groups to the alignment until the entire query set has been incorporated into the solution.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The initial tree describing the sequence relatedness is based on pairwise comparisons that may include heuristic pairwise alignment methods similar to FASTA.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Progressive alignment results are dependent on the choice of "most related" sequences and thus can be sensitive to inaccuracies in the initial pairwise alignments.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Most progressive multiple sequence alignment methods additionally weight the sequences in the query set according to their relatedness, which reduces the likelihood of making a poor choice of initial sequences and thus improves alignment accuracy.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Many variations of the Clustal progressive implementation are used for multiple sequence alignment, phylogenetic tree construction, and as input for protein structure prediction.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] A slower but more accurate variant of the progressive method is known as T-Coffee.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Iterative methods attempt to improve on the heavy dependence on the accuracy of the initial pairwise alignments, which is the weak point of the progressive methods.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Iterative methods optimize an objective function based on a selected alignment scoring method by assigning an initial global alignment and then realigning sequence subsets.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The realigned subsets are then themselves aligned to produce the next iteration's multiple sequence alignment.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Various ways of selecting the sequence subgroups and objective function are reviewed in.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Motif finding, also known as profile analysis, constructs global multiple sequence alignments that attempt to align short conserved sequence motifs among the sequences in the query set.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] This is usually done by first constructing a general global multiple sequence alignment, after which the highly conserved regions are isolated and used to construct a set of profile matrices.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The profile matrix for each conserved region is arranged like a scoring matrix but its frequency counts for each amino acid or nucleotide at each position are derived from the conserved region's character distribution rather than from a more general empirical distribution.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The profile matrices are then used to search other sequences for occurrences of the motif they characterize.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] In cases where the original data set contained a small number of sequences, or only highly related sequences, pseudocounts are added to normalize the character distributions represented in the motif.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] A variety of general optimization algorithms commonly used in computer science have also been applied to the multiple sequence alignment problem.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Genetic algorithms and simulated annealing have also been used in optimizing multiple sequence alignment scores as judged by a scoring function like the sum-of-pairs method.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] More complete details and software packages can be found in the main article multiple sequence alignment.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The Burrows–Wheeler transform has been successfully applied to fast short read alignment in popular tools such as Bowtie and BWA.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Structural alignments, which are usually specific to protein and sometimes RNA sequences, use information about the secondary and tertiary structure of the protein or RNA molecule to aid in aligning the sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Because both protein and RNA structure is more evolutionarily conserved than sequence, structural alignments can be more reliable between sequences that are very distantly related and that have diverged so extensively that sequence comparison cannot reliably detect their similarity.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Structural alignments are used as the "gold standard" in evaluating alignments for homology-based protein structure prediction because they explicitly align regions of the protein sequence that are structurally similar rather than relying exclusively on sequence information.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] However, clearly structural alignments cannot be used in structure prediction because at least one sequence in the query set is the target to be modeled, for which the structure is not known.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The DALI method, or distance matrix alignment, is a fragment-based method for constructing structural alignments based on contact similarity patterns between successive hexapeptides in the query sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] It can generate pairwise or multiple alignments and identify a query sequence's structural neighbors in the Protein Data Bank (PDB).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] It has been used to construct the FSSP structural alignment database (Fold classification based on Structure-Structure alignment of Proteins, or Families of Structurally Similar Proteins).
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] A DALI webserver can be accessed at DALI and the FSSP is located at The Dali Database.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] SSAP (sequential structure alignment program) is a dynamic programming-based method of structural alignment that uses atom-to-atom vectors in structure space as comparison points.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] It has been extended since its original description to include multiple as well as pairwise alignments, and has been used in the construction of the CATH (Class, Architecture, Topology, Homology) hierarchical database classification of protein folds.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The CATH database can be accessed at CATH Protein Structure Classification.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The combinatorial extension method of structural alignment generates a pairwise structural alignment by using local geometry to align short fragments of the two proteins being analyzed and then assembles these fragments into a larger alignment.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] A path from one protein structure state to the other is then traced through the matrix by extending the growing alignment one fragment at a time.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The optimal such path defines the combinatorial-extension alignment.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] A web-based server implementing the method and providing a database of pairwise alignments of structures in the Protein Data Bank is located at the Combinatorial Extension website.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Phylogenetics and sequence alignment are closely related fields due to the shared necessity of evaluating sequence relatedness.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The field of phylogenetics makes extensive use of sequence alignments in the construction and interpretation of phylogenetic trees, which are used to classify the evolutionary relationships between homologous genes represented in the genomes of divergent species.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The degree to which sequences in a query set differ is qualitatively related to the sequences' evolutionary distance from one another.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Roughly speaking, high sequence identity suggests that the sequences in question have a comparatively young most recent common ancestor, while low identity suggests that the divergence is more ancient.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Therefore, it does not account for possible difference among organisms or species in the rates of DNA repair or the possible functional conservation of specific regions in a sequence.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] More statistically accurate methods allow the evolutionary rate on each branch of the phylogenetic tree to vary, thus producing better estimates of coalescence times for genes.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Progressive multiple alignment techniques produce a phylogenetic tree by necessity because they incorporate sequences into the growing alignment in order of relatedness.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Other techniques that assemble multiple sequence alignments and phylogenetic trees score and sort trees first and calculate a multiple sequence alignment from the highest-scoring tree.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Commonly used methods of phylogenetic tree construction are mainly heuristic because the problem of selecting the optimal tree, like the problem of selecting the optimal multiple sequence alignment, is NP-hard.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Sequence alignments are useful in bioinformatics for identifying sequence similarity, producing phylogenetic trees, and developing homology models of protein structures.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] However, the biological relevance of sequence alignments is not always clear.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] In database searches such as BLAST, statistical methods can determine the likelihood of a particular alignment between sequences or sequence regions arising by chance given the size and composition of the database being searched.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] These values can vary significantly depending on the search space.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] In particular, the likelihood of finding a given alignment by chance increases if the database consists only of sequences from the same organism as the query sequence.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Repetitive sequences in the database or query can also distort both the search results and the assessment of statistical significance; BLAST automatically filters such repetitive sequences in the query to avoid apparent hits that are statistical artifacts.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Methods of statistical significance estimation for gapped sequence alignments are available in the literature.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Statistical significance indicates the probability that an alignment of a given quality could arise by chance, but does not indicate how much superior a given alignment is to alternative alignments of the same sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Measures of alignment credibility indicate the extent to which the best scoring alignments for a given pair of sequences are substantially similar.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Methods of alignment credibility estimation for gapped sequence alignments are available in the literature.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The choice of a scoring function that reflects biological or statistical observations about known sequences is important to producing good alignments.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Protein sequences are frequently aligned using substitution matrices that reflect the probabilities of given character-to-character substitutions.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] A series of matrices called PAM matrices (Point Accepted Mutation matrices, originally defined by Margaret Dayhoff and sometimes referred to as "Dayhoff matrices") explicitly encode evolutionary approximations regarding the rates and probabilities of particular amino acid mutations.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Another common series of scoring matrices, known as BLOSUM (Blocks Substitution Matrix), encodes empirically derived substitution probabilities.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Variants of both types of matrices are used to detect sequences with differing levels of divergence, thus allowing users of BLAST or FASTA to restrict searches to more closely related matches or expand to detect more divergent sequences.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Gap penalties account for the introduction of a gap - on the evolutionary model, an insertion or deletion mutation - in both nucleotide and protein sequences, and therefore the penalty values should be proportional to the expected rate of such mutations.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The quality of the alignments produced therefore depends on the quality of the scoring function.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] It can be very useful and instructive to try the same alignment several times with different choices for scoring matrix and/or gap penalty values and compare the results.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Regions where the solution is weak or non-unique can often be identified by observing which regions of the alignment are robust to variations in alignment parameters.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Sequenced RNA, such as expressed sequence tags and full-length mRNAs, can be aligned to a sequenced genome to find where there are genes and get information about alternative splicing and RNA editing.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Sequence alignment is also a part of genome assembly, where sequences are aligned to find overlap so that *contigs* (long stretches of sequence) can be formed.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Another use is SNP analysis, where sequences from different individuals are aligned to find single basepairs that are often different in a population.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The methods used for biological sequence alignment have also found applications in other fields, most notably in natural language processing and in social sciences, where the Needleman-Wunsch algorithm is usually referred to as Optimal matching.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Techniques that generate the set of elements from which words will be selected in natural-language generation algorithms have borrowed multiple sequence alignment techniques from bioinformatics to produce linguistic versions of computer-generated mathematical proofs.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] In the field of historical and comparative linguistics, sequence alignment has been used to partially automate the comparative method by which linguists traditionally reconstruct languages.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Business and marketing research has also applied multiple sequence alignment techniques in analyzing series of purchases over time.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] A more complete list of available software categorized by algorithm and alignment type is available at sequence alignment software, but common software tools used for general sequence alignment tasks include ClustalW2 and T-coffee for alignment, and BLAST and FASTA3x for database searching.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Commercial tools such as DNASTAR Lasergene, Geneious, and PatternHunter are also available.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Tools annotated as performing sequence alignment are listed in the bio.tools registry.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] Alignment algorithms and software can be directly compared to one another using a standardized set of benchmark reference multiple sequence alignments known as BAliBASE.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The data set consists of structural alignments, which can be considered a standard against which purely sequence-based methods are compared.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] The relative performance of many common alignment methods on frequently encountered alignment problems has been tabulated and selected results published online at BAliBASE.
[src:longest-common-subsequence/sequence-alignment] A comprehensive list of BAliBASE scores for many (currently 12) different alignment tools can be computed within the protein workbench STRAP.
